{{#demo-css}}
<h3>Component::<code>ui-item</code></h3>

<h4>Overview</h4>
<div class="row">
    <desc>
        The <prop>ui-item</prop> is the default list item. As the basis for all other items it defines a good number of key properties which include:
        <ul>
          <li>Layout and property definition of <prop>aspects</prop> and <prop>panes</prop></li>
          <li>The relative <prop>size</prop> of each item</li>
          <li>The <prop>skin</prop> to use for styling purposes</li>
          <li>A <prop>mood</prop> which simply sets CSS styling for some common mood types made popular by bootstrap</li>
          <li>Can be displayed as individual item or join up with other items as part of a <strong>list</strong>; it knows how to behave appropriately in either context</li>
        </ul>
    </desc>
</div>
<h4>CSS Layout</h4>
<p>
  This component uses CSS <i>flexbox</i> and is structured as follows:
</p>
<img src='images/ui-item-css.png'>
<p>
  This structure is partially assuming that you'll be using the <i>inline</i> form but if you use the <i>block</i> form then your text is inserted into the ".pane.centerPane" and the <prop>.title</prop> and <prop>.sub-heading</prop> spans will not be added (although you're free to add it yourself of course).
</p>
<br/>
<h4>Basic Example</h4>
<row>
  <widget>
    {{ui-item
      icon='envelope'
      title='Your Email'
      badgeRight=4
    }}
  </widget>
  <code>
    {{display-component componentName='ui-item'
      icon='envelope'
      title='Your Email'
      badgeRight=4
    }}
  </code>
  <description>
    A very simple example but a few quick points not to be missed:
    <ul>
      <li><prop>icon</prop> and <prop>title</prop> are examples of <i>aspects</i> we'd like displayed but do not have any reference to <i>pane</i>; instead this item type has certain defaults and assumes where these should go. These two properties could also be assigned explictly with <prop>iconLeft</prop> and <prop>titleCenter</prop>.</li>
      <li><prop>badgeRight</prop> is an example of stating both <i>aspect</i> and <i>pane</i></li>
      <li>the rightward facing chevron is the <prop>ui-item</prop> component setting the default value of <prop>iconRight</prop> to 'chevron-right'. </li>
    </ul>
  </description>
</row>
<row>
  <widget>
    {{#ui-item size='small'}}
      now for something completely different
    {{/ui-item}}
  </widget>
  <code>
    {{#display-component componentName='ui-item'}}
      now for something completely different
    {{/display-component}}
  </code>
  <description>
    The block style format is also available and provides universal freedom in how you style your items. This style for <i>items</i> has not been tested as much as the inline style so please send in a PR if you find any snafus.
  </description>
</row>

